widgets_values: Use checkpoints that are good at composition and poses and have a style that is easy for the OpenPose Preprocessor to extract poses from.The ore realistic the better geerally

When using an SDXL-based checkpoint, set 1 will be forced. Those are the values that SDXL has been trained on, so they're the best fit for it.

You can freely add new presets. The first 2 numbers in each line are used (1st- width, 2nd - height. You can write anything after that, and anything that isn't a number before and between the two numbers.

To add sets, you need to convert to nodes, copy one of the set nodes and connect it's output to the text list node. If you run out of connections, use a text list concatenate node
Most important here are descriptions of poses, interactions, framing and perspective. Only the Pose image extracted from this will be used later with ControlNet

The selected preset is concatenated in front of the main prompt

When adding new presets, they should be separated by a "#" character
The preset text should begin any number of new lines below. The line with '#' and all subsequent empty lines are removed before combining with the main prompt

Instead of generating an image, you can load one here and pass it into the preprocessor for photos or the pose and overlay inputs that the output of the preprocessor goes to for openpose images.

By setting width you can resize to the loaded image to that width while keeping its proportions.

The original and final size will be outputted on the 'Size info' pin and can be inspected with a 'show text' node.
(it has to be separate from the group node as the field is not displayed if included in a group node)

You can switch subject connections to switch their places

Can't set scheduler for multiple nodes at once other than with a primitive and you can't hide the additional widgets it comes with so enjoy ability to randomize your schedulers for each generation
Remove ControlNet if you don't plan using a high enough denoising in 2nd step to actually need it as it slows sampling down

Samples with the latent couple method - only uses the global sampler's LoRAs and combines all prompts bound to their respective regions. 

Good if you set denoising low and only want to refine some details on the upscaled image. Fast

Alternative 2nd pass

Uses regional sampling like in 1st pass, so it keeps subject LoRAs and their regions.

Good with high denoising where you might need to restore some features on the LoRA characters, but slower
Once you queue with a mask drawn, this will show you a clearer picture of the drawn mask

After a picture appears here:
Right-click -> Open in MaskEditor

Mask just one of the characters.
use scroll wheel to resize brush
right-click to erase

for controlnet use an openpose model

Currently, there is no SDXL support as the so far trained controlnet models are awful. Once they're good (openpose specifically) you can call me up.
Will combine the prompt preset with whatever you add here, then pass that to subject nodes that will concatenate this in front of their prompts

This workflow lets you to split the canvas in two separate sampling regions allowing for use of different LoRA models on each region without them infuencing one another. OpenPose Controlnet ensures consistency of perspective between subject regions and allows for seamless close and complex interaction between characters like hugs.

#############################################################################
 ---------------------------------HOW TO USE---------------------------------
#############################################################################
(You will get a some errors using this workflow, it's just a part of how it works)

 1) Generate images focusing on the desired pose in Group I
 2) Mute group I (right-click -> Set Group Notes to Never)
 3) Queue prompt, wait for preprocessor to finish and for a picture to appear in the Mask Editor node (purple). You can cancel then.
 4) If the pose is badly detected, go back to step #2
 5) Draw a mask in the Mask Editor
 6) Set the global and subject promts and LoRAs
 7) Queue prompt

Alternatively, instead of pregenerating an image in group I, you can use the 'Image Load and Resize to Width' node as described in the attached note

- Sometimes you may need to queue and cancel twice to see some effects
- instead of muting the entire group I, you can just mute the 1st pass there with ctrl+m
- for more information on specific parts of the workflow refer to attached notes


You can make 2 characters from different LoRA or 1 character, but with clothes (all or some) from another one, etc, even different art styles, though that may not mix very well
